Juliana Taiwo-Obalonye President Muhammadu Buhari has denied deriding Nigerian youths during a question and answer session at the Commonwealth Business Forum in London on Wednesday. The President accused those he described as “manipulators and twisters of statements” as misrepresenting his comment. The President had earlier given a keynote address on ‘Making Business Easier Between Commonwealth Countries’. The Special Adviser to the President on Media and Publicity, Femi Adesina, in a statement recalled that Buhari had cause to talk about some Nigerian youths, where he said: “We have a very young population; our population is estimated conservatively to be 180 million. More than 60 per cent of the population is below the age of 30. A lot of them have not been to school and they are claiming that Nigeria has been an oil producing country, therefore they should sit and do nothing and get housing, healthcare and education free.” The press statement in response to the comment controversy read: